<PageTitle>Help</PageTitle>

<Markdown>
    ## SSH Connection
    
    You can log in to the Raspberry PI with any terminal that supports SSH. The password at the time of writing is `admin`.
    
    ```sh
    ssh admin@shaker.local
    ```
    
    You will be prompted for a password which is _not_ visible when you type it. The password is mentioned above.
    
    >> **Note:** The raspberry PI hosts its own DNS server, resolving `shaker.local` to the gateway IP adress of the wifi hotspot/access point. If the raspberry PI is access via the lan port, then the IP adress is assigned by the respective router and **not** `192.168.1.1`.
    
    ## Deployment
    
    In the admins home folder is a script called `deploy.sh`. It will pull the latest source code from the github 
    repository, build and publish the application and restart the systemd service.
    
    If the source code is moved - **be aware of the [AGPL license](https://github.com/ACaaD/acaad.ctrl.svc?tab=AGPL-3.0-1-ov-file) of the downstream dependency [ACaaD](https://github.com/ACaaD) (!)** - this is the place that must be adjusted.
    
    Assuming the raspi is connected to the internet, you can run a deployment by executing:
    
    ```sh
    ssh admin@shaker.local
    cd ~ # Test
    ./deploy.sh
    ```
    
    The process takes between 30 and 60 seconds.
    
    ## File Locations
    
    The following list shows important file locations on the Raspberry PI.
    
    | File | Location | Description |
    |--|--|--|
    | SystemD Service | `/etc/systemd/system/shaker.service` | The `systemd` unit file. Enabled to auto start the app. |
    | App Secrets | `/etc/shaker/secrets` | App configuration, Influx credentials |
    | OtelCol Config | `/etc/otelcol/config.yaml` | OpenTelemetry Collector configuration file. |
    
    This is not rendered for some reason.
    Basic understanding of Linux is assumed.
    
    ## InfluxDB Credentials
    
    The app writes measured GForces (and baseline data/metadata) to an `InfluxDB` instance hosted on the Raspberry PI.
    
    The Influx UI can visualize this data. The following credentials are used at the time of writing:
    
    **Host:** [`http://shaker.local:8086`](http://shaker.local:8086)
    **Username:** `admin`
    **Password:** `adminadmin`
    **Token:** `@influxOptions.Value.Token`
</Markdown>

